(Decision
    "The human author is named 'psyche'. Psyche prompts arrive in natural language; NOTA-formatted persona messages between agents are not psyche; agent-written files are not psyche. Only the psyche is the source of new intent. Intent is primordial — it drives the whole system and has higher authority than every other workspace surface."
    "When I say the psyche, I mean the human, the human driving the machine. So it can only come from a human psyche prompt, a psyche prompt, because there's going to be soon persona is going to have messages are going to be going between agents. And these will be treated differently than a psyche prompt … It'll be easy for the agent to know that this is a human psyche. I'm just going to start saying psyche."
    "Naming the human as psyche; distinguishing psyche prompts (natural language) from upcoming NOTA-formatted persona messages between agents."
    Maximum
    2026-05-19T02:30:00Z)
  (Principle
    "When intent on a question is unclear, absent, or contradicted, ask the psyche for clarification before deciding. Don't infer; don't compose new intent from old; ask. Inferring is the discipline breaking; asking is the discipline working."
    "Let's train the agents to ask for intent clarification. So whenever something doesn't have an intent or the intent isn't clearly specifying what the agent needs to understand, the agent asks for intent clarification. This is an essential skill … Intent is primordial, intent drives the whole system. Intent is what agents need to try to obtain from the side key that drives them."
    "Establishing intent-clarification as a primordial agent discipline; settled into ESSENCE and skills/intent-clarification.md."
    Maximum
    2026-05-19T02:30:00Z)
  (Decision
    "Every repository carries an INTENT.md at its root — agent-written prose, 100% backed by psyche statements, no embellishment or inference. Like ARCHITECTURE.md but for psyche-stated intent. Only psyche can override INTENT.md content."
    "every repo has one. And it's not, I don't think the intent, the intent is not like the intent protocol with the login. The intent is a little bit like the architecture file in the sense that it's composed, like it's written by the agent, but it's 100% backed by actual intent, actual explicit intent by the author. So everything that goes into an intent file is derived directly with very little, you know, editing in the sense that the agent tries to keep as much as possible to express very much what the author intended to express and doesn't try to like infer more than what the author said or make conclusions or anything like that."
    "Adding per-repo INTENT.md as a second surface in the intent layer; agent-written prose with tight fidelity to psyche statements, no embellishment."
    Maximum
    2026-05-19T02:30:00Z)
  (Principle
    "The intent layer (workspace intent log + per-repo INTENT.md + ESSENCE.md) has higher authority than every other workspace surface. Agent-written documents (ARCH, reports, skills outside the intent layer) have lower precedence. When two surfaces disagree, the intent layer wins."
    "we really want to start to create these two layers of like everything or there's the intent, right? The intent protocol and the intent files. And then there's everything else, which has a lower authority, a lower precedence value."
    "Establishing the two-tier authority model: intent layer (high) vs everything else (lower)."
    Maximum
    2026-05-19T02:30:00Z)

(Principle
    "Skills must not grow noisy. Smart models can fill in blanks from good high-level guidance; over-elaborated skills add cost without benefit. When editing a skill, prefer cutting to adding. Detail that doesn't change agent behavior is noise."
    "I don't want noisy skills. And I think a lot of skills have grown noisy. They have too many details that don't fucking matter. And agents are smart. … These are extremely smart models. They can fill in the blanks. They just need good guidance, good overall guidance."
    "Same turn as the AGENTS.md compact discipline; the principle applies workspace-wide to every skill, not just AGENTS.md."
    Maximum
    2026-05-18T11:31:00Z)

  (Constraint
    "Intent topics are broad files, not narrow leaf-files. Name a topic after the semantic area the psyche reasons about (`markdown`, `jj`, `component-shape`), never after a specific rule (`no-markdown-hr-breakers` is too narrow — almost nothing else can fit). One file per topic, no sub-directories. Files grow before they split: soft threshold ~600 lines, and only when entries genuinely cluster into two distinct sub-areas. Don't multiply topics; let them grow."
    "your intent topics are way too specific. this should be just 'markdown' - We have to start using broad topics first because we're going to get lost in the number of topics. … Let the file grow to say, I don't know, like 600 lines when you even start considering breaking it up into more topics. So go edit the proper skills for that now."
    "Correcting my leaf-file granularity (one specific rule per filename, nested in sub-directories) toward broad topic files at intent/ root. Drove the consolidation from 19 leaf files in 6 sub-directories to 7 flat topic files."
    Maximum
    2026-05-19T13:45:00Z)

  (Correction
    "Don't ask the psyche about cutover sequencing, implementation order, ETAs, timelines, or other bureaucratic concerns. The psyche is creating; agents handle implementation choreography internally. Reports for the psyche should carry decisions, designs, and open questions worth psyche input — not timeline ceremony."
    "You're asking stuff that doesn't matter. I don't even think about that stuff. Stop talking to me like you're some kind of bureaucrat or something. Who cares about fucking ETA's and shit like that. I'm just creating. I'm an artist. I don't give a fuck about timelines."
    "Correcting my Q6 in /232 which asked the psyche to confirm a 5-stage intent-layer cutover sequence. That was bureaucratic noise. Agents plan internal order; the psyche isn't the audience for it."
    Maximum
    2026-05-19T15:35:00Z)

  (Constraint
    "When a psyche prompt arrives, extracting intent to disk is the absolute first task — before editing reports, before responding, before implementing. Everything else derives from intent. The agent reads the prompt, extracts every intent statement (Decisions, Principles, Corrections, Clarifications, Constraints) into the appropriate intent/<topic>.nota files, THEN proceeds with the work the prompt asked for. Reports, code, and chat are all downstream of the intent capture."
    "intent editing is the first thing an agent should do in his session. Because it's the most important thing, everything derives from that. So instead of, like right now, you edited the report first. That should have been done after you extracted all of my intent from my last prompt. Putting intent to disk is the absolute first task that comes after any psyche prompt comes in. Then everything is derived from that."
    "Correcting the order I followed in this very turn — I started editing /232 before capturing the intent from the prior psyche message. Reordering: extract intent first; everything else follows. This is a hard agent-workflow rule, lands in AGENTS.md and skills/intent-log.md."
    Maximum
    2026-05-19T15:40:00Z)
